  <meta property="og:description" content="In my previous post, I discussed how to do a quick sentiment analysis on Twitter data using R's twitteR and sentiment package. However the&nbsp;sentiment package is a old package and not support by CRAN anymore, but I found a really good package for sentiment analysis called syuzhet on Dr. Matthew Jockers' website. In this post I will do a sentiment analysis using this syuzhet package on J.R.R. Tolkien's The Lord of the Rings Trilogy — One of my favorite book of all time.



via GIPHY

Bad thing is I forget where I found the txt files for the books, but I'm sure you can easily find it somewhere online.
Preliminary Processing
First lets load all the packaged
library(syuzhet)
library(tm)
library(wordcloud)
library(ggplot2)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(dplyr)
library(RCurl)
library(stringr)
library(readr)
library(reshape2)
library(gridExtra)
library(extrafont)

Assume we got the books in txt file type and has been placed in the working folder, we can use read_lines function to read it into a character file. Let's start with The Fellowship of the Ring.
LOR1_raw = read_lines(The Fellowship of the Ring.txt) # read txt file
head(LOR1_raw)

## [1] Chapter 01                                                                                                                                                                                        
## [2] A Long-expected Party                                                                                                                                                                             
## [3] <U+00A1><U+00A1>                                                                                                                                                                                  
## [4]                                                                                                                                                                                                   
## [5] When Mr. Bilbo Baggins of Bag End announced that he would shortly be celebrating his eleventy-first birthday with a party of special magnificence, there was much talk and excitement in Hobbiton.
## [6] 

Two things: We have some weird characters in the data and there are empty lines, we do want them affect our analysis
LOR1_raw = iconv(LOR1_raw, latin1, ASCII, sub=) # remove the non english characters in the book
LOR1 = LOR1_raw[which(LOR1_raw !=)] # remove the empty lines
head(LOR1,3)

## [1] Chapter 01                                                                                                                                                                                        
## [2] A Long-expected Party                                                                                                                                                                             
## [3] When Mr. Bilbo Baggins of Bag End announced that he would shortly be celebrating his eleventy-first birthday with a party of special magnificence, there was much talk and excitement in Hobbiton.

Much better now. Each element is a paragraph of the book, it will be easy for us to search through it.
The syuzhet Package
The get_nrc_sentiment function of syuzhet package uses National Research Council Canada (NRC)'s sentiment dictionary to calculate the presence of eight different emotions and their corresponding valence in a text file. The output of this function will be a data frame where each row represents a sentence from the original file. The columns include one for each emotion type was well as a positive or negative valence. Let's try some sampe examples first.
get_nrc_sentiment(what a lovely little young girl)

##   anger anticipation disgust fear joy sadness surprise trust negative
## 1     0            2       0    0   2       1        2     1        0
##   positive
## 1        2

Pretty neat, eh? Now we can apply it on our book
LOR1nrc <- cbind(parag = seq_along(LOR1), get_nrc_sentiment(LOR1))
LOR1nrc$negative = LOR1nrc$negative * (-1) # change negative score to negative
LOR1byline <- LOR1nrc %>% select(-positive, -negative) %>% 
  melt(id = c(parag))
head(LOR1byline)

##   parag variable value
## 1     1    anger     0
## 2     2    anger     0
## 3     3    anger     0
## 4     4    anger     2
## 5     5    anger     0
## 6     6    anger     1

Above code will give us a summary score of positive and negative scores of each paragraph individually. Now we can use ggplot2 to visualized the sentiment of this book. In this post I will use a beta version of ggplot2 package from Hadely Wickman's github. This version has the title and subtitle support and I just wanna try it out.
Add Different Fonts and Subtitles for ggplot2 Charts
First we need install beta version of ggplot2 from Hadely Wickman's github
devtools::install_github(hadley/ggplot2)

Then let's import some more fonts from our system using font_import() function from extrafont package
font_import()

This may take a while, and once you're done, you can use the following command to output a font matrix, it is much easier if we can see all the font then pick the font we like the most.
fonttable = fonttable()
fonttable = as.data.frame(unique(fonttable$FamilyName))
names(fonttable)[1] = FamilyName
a = rep(1:20, 9)
b = rep(1:9, each = 20)
fonttable$row = a[1:179]
fonttable$col= b[1:179]

ggplot(fonttable, aes(x=col, y=row)) + geom_text(aes(label=FamilyName, family=FamilyName))



Let's say we like Franklin Gothic Medium, the we can call it using
ff = fonts()
ff[58]

## [1] Franklin Gothic Medium

Here we go, just add labs() in your ggplot and text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12 into your theme parameters, you can generate the nice looking ggplot with customized fonts and subtitles.
tt = Various Sentiments in 'The Fellowship of the Ring'
stt = Line chart of different sentiments. The X-axis represents the paragraph number so in this case the narrative time and the Y-axis represents the score of the sentiment.
stt <- paste0(strwrap(stt, 90), sep=, collapse=\n)
cptn = thinkdatascience.com | Michael Yan


ggplot(data = LOR1byline %>% filter(parag <= 100), aes(x = parag, y = value, color = variable)) +
  geom_line(size=0.5, alpha = 0.8) + 
  labs(title = tt, subtitle = stt,  caption = cptn, x = Narrative Time, y = Sentiment) +
  theme( text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12),
         legend.title = element_blank(),
         plot.title = element_text(colour=black, size = 12, face = bold),
         legend.position=right) 

## Error in filter(., parag <= 100): object 'parag' not found

Generate Charts for Sentiment
In the above line chart I only looking at the first 100 paragraphs of the book. It's useful but it's too granular to do the analysis. Most of the cases we only care about the binary sentiment Positive or Negative, the get_sentiment functon of syuzhet provides the simple positive or negative scores using different kinds of methodology.
LOR1sentiment =data.frame(cbind(parag = seq_along(LOR1), senti = get_sentiment(LOR1, method = afinn)))
head(LOR1sentiment)

##   parag senti
## 1     1     0
## 2     2     0
## 3     3     6
## 4     4    14
## 5     5    -1
## 6     6     4

The support method for this function includes

	afinn from Finn and Nielsen
	bing from Bing Liu and collaborators
	nrc from Saif Mohammad and Peter Turney
	standford from Manning, Christopher D., et al

Dr. Matthew Jockers did a little test by himself here and he found out that in his experiment, afinn and bing method yields the best result. So in this post I will use afinn method, but feel free to test different methods by yourself.

I plotted the sentiment using bar chart and made some annotation of the high and low point, if you read the book or saw the movie, those peaks and dips are correct.
tt = Positive and Negative Sentiment in 'The Fellowship of the Ring'
stt = Line chart of positive and negative sentiment. The X-axis represents the paragraph number so in this case the narrative time and the Y-axis represents the score of the sentiment.
stt <- paste0(strwrap(stt, 90), sep=, collapse=\n)
cptn = thinkdatascience.com | Michael Yan

annotext <- data.frame(x = c(3742, 344, 1756, 292, 2666, 1108), y = c(-23,-18,-17,18,16,15), 
                           label = c(Frodo left Sam, Gandalf tells Frodo stories about the ring,Frodo injured by NazgÃ»l, 
                                     Gandalf describes Bilbo,Sam's memory of Shire, Fellowship in Elf's forest))

ggplot(data = LOR1sentiment, aes(x = parag, y = senti, fill = senti)) +
  geom_bar(stat = identity, position = dodge,size = 5) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = tt, subtitle = stt,  caption = cptn, x = Narrative Time, y = Sentiment) +
  theme( text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
         plot.title = element_text(colour=black, size = 12, face = bold),
         strip.text.x = element_text(size=15, face=bold, colour = black),
         strip.text.y = element_text(size=25, face=bold, colour = black),
         legend.position=right) +scale_fill_gradient( low=blue, high=orange) +
         geom_text(data = annotext, aes(x,y,label=label), hjust = 0.5, size = 3, inherit.aes = FALSE) 



Now lets do the same thing on the second and third book





I noticed that in most cases, our sentiment analysis got the result correctly. Everytime when Sam or others talked about Shire, there is a spike in the positive sentiment. Although there is one draw back in the alogirithm. If we look at The Two Towers, Saruman's Defeat was marked as negative sentiment. This is because the algorithm itself are not smart enough to distingusih between good guys and bad guys. If the bad guy is have a good time, the algorithm will think it is a good thing.



via GIPHY
Fourier Transformation of Time
The above three plots are pretty but it is hard to compare them because they all have different length and the positive and negative sentiment are seprated so it is hard to see the cumulative sentiment flow. It is also hard to compare book to book because each book will have different length. But luckliy we have a tool called Fourier Transformation to normalize the length of the x-axis. Recall the formula below:

\[\hat{f}(\xi) = \sum_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{-2\pi i x \xi}dx\]

The author of syuzhet package integrated this feature into the function called get_transformed_values and it also has a low pass filter. We can think low pass filter as a “noise filter”. The lower the number it is, the smoothier curve we will get. In this post I used low_pass_size = 3 parameter value, same as Dr. Jockers used in his paper.
tt = Fourier Transformed Sentiment in 'The Fellowship of the Ring'
cptn = thinkdatascience.com | Michael Yan

LOR1ft <- as.numeric(get_transformed_values(LOR1sentiment$senti, 
                                            low_pass_size = 3,
                                            scale_vals = TRUE,
                                            scale_range = FALSE))
LOR1ft <- data.frame(cbind(linenumber = seq_along(LOR1ft), ft = LOR1ft))

ggplot(data = LOR1ft, aes(x = linenumber, y = ft)) +
  geom_bar(stat = identity, alpha = 0.8, color = green3, fill = green3) +
  labs(title = tt, caption = cptn, x = Narrative Time, y = Fourier Transformed Value) +
  theme( text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
         plot.title = element_text(colour=black, size = 12, face = bold),
         strip.text.x = element_text(size=15, face=bold, colour = black),
         strip.text.y = element_text(size=25, face=bold, colour = black),
         legend.position=right)



Now the sentiment flow can be seen much clearly, and we can easily compare the different books



It's quite a journey to &nbsp;read Lord of the Rings trilogy, right? But it is good we have a happy ending! Be careful to run this on every book you are going to read — spoiler alert!

						window.open(url, "popupwindow", "scrollbars=yes,width=1080,height=760");
						return true;
					}
				} else {
					alert("Please enter email address");
					jQuery(ref).find('input[name="data[Widget][email]"]').focus();
					return false;
				}
			}
		</script>

         <h1 class="entry-title">Sentiment Analysis of Lord of the Rings Trilogy using R and syuzhet package</h1> 
         <div class="entry-meta"> 
          <span class="posted-on">Posted on <a href="http://thinkdatascience.com/sentiment-analysis-of-lord-of-the-rings-trilogy-using-r-and-syuzhet-package/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2016-04-05T10:40:54+00:00">April 5, 2016</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-04-05T10:58:45+00:00">April 5, 2016</time></a></span>
          <span class="byline"> by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://thinkdatascience.com/author/wwwjk366/">Michael Yan</a></span></span> 
         </div>
         <!-- .entry-meta --> 
        </header>
        <!-- .entry-header --> 
        <div id="featured-image"> 
         <img width="500" height="281" src="http://thinkdatascience.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/63735910.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full wp-post-image" alt="63735910" srcset="http://thinkdatascience.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/63735910.jpg 500w, http://thinkdatascience.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/63735910-300x169.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px"> 
        </div> 
        <div class="entry-content"> 
         <p>In my previous post, I discussed how to do a quick sentiment analysis on Twitter data using R’s <strong>twitteR</strong> and <strong>sentiment</strong> package. However the&nbsp;<strong>sentiment</strong> package is a old package and not support by CRAN anymore, but I found a really good package for sentiment analysis called <strong>syuzhet</strong> on Dr. Matthew Jockers’ <a href="http://www.matthewjockers.net/">website</a>. In this post I will do a sentiment analysis using this <strong>syuzhet</strong> package on <em>J.R.R. Tolkien’s The Lord of the Rings Trilogy</em> — One of my favorite book of all time.</p> 
         <p><iframe width="480" height="244" src="//giphy.com/embed/yUSLvx5GW5YgU" frameborder="0" class="giphy-embed" allowfullscreen></iframe></p> 
         <p><a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/the-lord-of-rings-yUSLvx5GW5YgU">via GIPHY</a></p> 
         <p>Bad thing is I forget where I found the txt files for the books, but I’m sure you can easily find it somewhere online.</p> 
         <h2>Preliminary Processing</h2> 
         <p>First lets load all the packaged</p>

         <p>Much better now. Each element is a paragraph of the book, it will be easy for us to search through it.</p> 
         <h2>The syuzhet Package</h2> 
         <p>The <code>get_nrc_sentiment</code> function of syuzhet package uses National Research Council Canada (NRC)’s sentiment dictionary to calculate the presence of eight different emotions and their corresponding valence in a text file. The output of this function will be a data frame where each row represents a sentence from the original file. The columns include one for each emotion type was well as a positive or negative valence. Let’s try some sampe examples first.</p>

         <p>Above code will give us a summary score of positive and negative scores of each paragraph individually. Now we can use ggplot2 to visualized the sentiment of this book. In this post I will use a beta version of ggplot2 package from Hadely Wickman’s github. This version has the title and subtitle support and I just wanna try it out.</p>

  labs(title = tt, subtitle = stt,  caption = cptn, x = "Narrative Time", y = "Sentiment") +
  theme( text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12),
         legend.title = element_blank(),
         plot.title = element_text(colour="black", size = 12, face = "bold"),

         <h2>Generate Charts for Sentiment</h2> 
         <p>In the above line chart I only looking at the first 100 paragraphs of the book. It’s useful but it’s too granular to do the analysis. Most of the cases we only care about the binary sentiment <em>Positive</em> or <em>Negative</em>, the <code>get_sentiment</code> functon of <strong>syuzhet</strong> provides the simple positive or negative scores using different kinds of methodology.</p>

         <!-- [Format Time: 0.0002 seconds] --> 
         <p>The support method for this function includes</p> 
         <ul> 
          <li><code>afinn</code> from <a href="http://www2.imm.dtu.dk/pubdb/views/publication_details.php?id=6010">Finn and Nielsen</a></li> 
          <li><code>bing</code> from <a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/%7Eliub/FBS/sentiment-analysis.html">Bing Liu and collaborators</a></li> 
          <li><code>nrc</code> from <a href="http://saifmohammad.com/WebPages/NRC-Emotion-Lexicon.htm">Saif Mohammad and Peter Turney</a></li> 
          <li><code>standford</code> from <a href="http://nlp.stanford.edu/software/corenlp.shtml">Manning, Christopher D., et al</a></li> 
         </ul> 
         <p>Dr. Matthew Jockers did a little test by himself <a href="http://www.matthewjockers.net/2015/04/01/my-sentiments-exactly/">here</a> and he found out that in his experiment, <code>afinn</code> and <code>bing</code> method yields the best result. So in this post I will use <code>afinn</code> method, but feel free to test different methods by yourself.</p> 
         <p>I plotted the sentiment using bar chart and made some annotation of the high and low point, if you read the book or saw the movie, those peaks and dips are correct.</p>

         <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-12"></p> 
         <p>Now lets do the same thing on the second and third book</p> 
         <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-14"></p> 
         <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-16"></p> 
         <p>I noticed that in most cases, our sentiment analysis got the result correctly. Everytime when Sam or others talked about Shire, there is a spike in the positive sentiment. Although there is one draw back in the alogirithm. If we look at <em>The Two Towers</em>, Saruman’s Defeat was marked as negative sentiment. This is because the algorithm itself are not smart enough to distingusih between good guys and bad guys. If the bad guy is have a good time, the algorithm will think it is a good thing.</p> 
         <p><iframe width="480" height="270" src="//giphy.com/embed/s44UgIuha27Ru" frameborder="0" class="giphy-embed" allowfullscreen></iframe></p> 
         <p><a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/request-lee-stabilization-s44UgIuha27Ru">via GIPHY</a></p> 
         <h2>Fourier Transformation of Time</h2> 
         <p>The above three plots are pretty but it is hard to compare them because they all have different length and the positive and negative sentiment are seprated so it is hard to see the cumulative sentiment flow. It is also hard to compare book to book because each book will have different length. But luckliy we have a tool called <em>Fourier Transformation</em> to normalize the length of the x-axis. Recall the formula below:</p> 
         <p>\[\hat{f}(\xi) = \sum_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)e^{-2\pi i x \xi}dx\]</p> 
         <p>The author of <code>syuzhet</code> package integrated this feature into the function called <code>get_transformed_values</code> and it also has a low pass filter. We can think low pass filter as a “noise filter”. The lower the number it is, the smoothier curve we will get. In this post I used <code>low_pass_size = 3</code> parameter value, same as Dr. Jockers used in his paper.</p>

          <div class="crayon-plain-wrap">
           <textarea wrap="soft" class="crayon-plain print-no" data-settings="dblclick" readonly style="-moz-tab-size:4; -o-tab-size:4; -webkit-tab-size:4; tab-size:4; font-size: 12px !important; line-height: 15px !important;">
tt = "Fourier Transformed Sentiment in 'The Fellowship of the Ring'"
cptn = "thinkdatascience.com | Michael Yan"

LOR1ft &amp;lt;- as.numeric(get_transformed_values(LOR1sentiment$senti, 
                                            low_pass_size = 3,
                                            scale_vals = TRUE,
                                            scale_range = FALSE))
LOR1ft &amp;lt;- data.frame(cbind(linenumber = seq_along(LOR1ft), ft = LOR1ft))

ggplot(data = LOR1ft, aes(x = linenumber, y = ft)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", alpha = 0.8, color = "green3", fill = "green3") +
  labs(title = tt, caption = cptn, x = "Narrative Time", y = "Fourier Transformed Value") +
  theme( text = element_text(family = ff[58], size = 12),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
         plot.title = element_text(colour="black", size = 12, face = "bold"),
         strip.text.x = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour = "black"),
         strip.text.y = element_text(size=25, face="bold", colour = "black"),
         legend.position="right")
</textarea>

         <p>Now the sentiment flow can be seen much clearly, and we can easily compare the different books</p> 
         <p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-18"></p> 
         <p>It’s quite a journey to &nbsp;read <em>Lord of the Rings</em> trilogy, right? But it is good we have a happy ending! Be careful to run this on every book you are going to read — spoiler alert!</p>
